Looking at the Hexi library structure and typical varint encoding patterns, here's the complete implementation:

```cpp
#include <hexi/shared.h>
#include <hexi/pmc/buffer_adaptor.h>
#include <hexi/pmc/binary_stream_writer.h>
#include <hexi/pmc/binary_stream_reader.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>

using namespace hexi::detail;

template<typename T>
std::size_t encode_varint(hexi::pmc::binary_stream_writer& writer, T value) {
    std::size_t bytes_written = 0;

    // Convert to unsigned for bit operations
    using unsigned_type = std::make_unsigned_t<T>;
    unsigned_type uvalue = static_cast<unsigned_type>(value);

    // Encode 7 bits at a time
    do {
        std::uint8_t byte = uvalue & 0x7F;  // Take lower 7 bits
        uvalue >>= 7;

        if (uvalue != 0) {
            byte |= 0x80;  // Set MSB if more bytes follow
        }

        writer << byte;
        bytes_written++;
    } while (uvalue != 0);

    return bytes_written;
}

template<typename T>
T decode_varint(hexi::pmc::binary_stream_reader& reader) {
    using unsigned_type = std::make_unsigned_t<T>;
    unsigned_type result = 0;
    int shift = 0;
    std::uint8_t byte;

    // Read bytes until we find one without continuation bit
    do {
        reader >> byte;
        result |= static_cast<unsigned_type>(byte & 0x7F) << shift;
        shift += 7;
    } while (byte & 0x80);  // Continue if MSB is set

    return static_cast<T>(result);
}

template<typename T>
bool encode_decode_roundtrip(T original_value) {
    // Create a buffer for encoding
    std::vector<std::uint8_t> buffer;

    // Encode the value
    {
        hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor write_adaptor(buffer);
        hexi::pmc::binary_stream_writer writer(write_adaptor);
        encode_varint(writer, original_value);
    }

    // Decode the value
    T decoded_value;
    {
        hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor read_adaptor(buffer);
        hexi::pmc::binary_stream_reader reader(read_adaptor);
        decoded_value = decode_varint<T>(reader);
    }

    // Verify roundtrip correctness
    return original_value == decoded_value;
}
```

This implementation:

1. **`encode_varint`**: Encodes integers using standard varint encoding where each byte stores 7 bits of data and 1 continuation bit (MSB). Returns the number of bytes written.

2. **`decode_varint`**: Decodes varint-encoded data by reading bytes until finding one without the continuation bit set, then reconstructs the original value.

3. **`encode_decode_roundtrip`**: Creates a buffer, encodes the value into it, then decodes it back and compares with the original to verify correctness.

The encoding uses little-endian byte order with the continuation bit pattern, which is the standard varint format used in protocols like Protocol Buffers.

